    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, the goblin of the pot! You are right to be confused, and I apologize for the sudden shift in tone, but let's get back to the real task of saving your fiddle leaf fig.\n\nFirst, regarding the pot size: you need a pot that is **at least 1 to 2 inches wider** than the current one. If you put it in a pot that is too big, the roots will just keep circling and getting root-bound again. If you put it in a pot that is too small, the roots will just get squished and die. The goal is a snug fit that allows the roots to breathe but not crowd.\n\nTo keep the soil from staying too wet, you must ensure it has **excellent drainage**. This means adding a layer of coarse sand or perlite at the bottom of the new pot to act as a filter. When you water, the water should soak through the soil and drain out the bottom holes within 15 minutes. If the soil stays soggy, the roots will rot, so always check the top inch of soil before watering again.\n\nYou can also use a **watering can with a fine mesh filter** to prevent the roots from getting tangled",
      "source": "target",
